post_text: The NI Music Booster Club is looking for members. This energetic group hosts the HS Breakfast Concert, puts on a Variety Show and a few other fundraisers throughout the year. post_text:
We will be holding a week of practice for tryouts for the year. If you are interested in football and/or basketball cheerleading, please plan on attending practice at the football field beginning next week Monday, August 10th from 6:30 to 7:30 pm. All efforts should be made to be in attendance; however, tryout materials can be provided virtually along with a virtual submission of a tryout if the student is unable to make the appointed time.

Anyone interested in being the mascot for football and/or basketball should also plan on attending.

Try-outs will be held Monday, August 17th at 4:30 pm in the high school auditorium. Students will try out in groups of three and will be socially distant on the stage.

If interested please come to practices or contact cheer coach Melissa Bennett at melissa.bennett@northiowa.org.

We will have camp for all 7th-12th grade volleyball players on Monday, August 3rd through Wednesday, August 5th. Camp will run from 8:00-10:00 am and 10:30-12:30pm each of those days. Players are encouraged to bring their own snacks for the break and a water bottle for both sessions.

We will take our 9th-12th grade volleyball players to Lake Mills for a competition team camp on Thursday, August 6th and Friday, August 7th. Due to COVID-19 concerns, no fans will be allowed at the team camp in Lake Mills.

Practice will begin officially on Monday, August 10th with strength and conditioning at 7:00 am.

post_text: There will be a no-cost cross country camp open to every middle or high school boy and girl in the North Iowa school district starting on August 3rd, meeting on the east side of the school by the main gymnasium entrance at 9 AM. The camp will run from Monday through Friday and will roughly be an hour in length each day. Any athlete that is interested in running or finding out more about cross country is encouraged to attend. Dress for activity and bring a good pair of running shoes. Official cross country practice for high school athletes will begin on the 10th of August at 9:00 AM - meeting in the North Gym lobby in Buffalo Center. Middle school practice will begin the first day of middle school at 3:45 - at the same location as the high school practice. Please bring a completed athletic physical to the first day of practice. If you have any questions please contact Jonathan Potter at 641-562-2890.

To the North Iowa Community,

Some baseball players have reported symptoms that are requiring testing for COVID 19. The testing will be completed. At this time out of caution and with the guidance of the public health department, North Iowa will be suspending baseball activities until at least Monday, June 29th. As more information is gathered, decisions will be passed along to the community. Softball will continue to have practice at this time.

Please continue to follow health guidelines including staying home when sick, social distancing, and regular hand washing.

We are pleased to announce that North Iowa High School will be playing baseball and softball this summer! Practice will begin June 1st for student athletes with games beginning the week of the 15th. Keep in mind that we are working as efficiently as possible to get game changes on the schedule so check the North Iowa homepage and Rschools calendar frequently.

There will be guidelines set up by the state as well as our school district to keep athletes, coaches, umpires and spectators safe. More information will be out soon regarding these guidelines. This news is no doubt a morale booster for our coaches and student athletes who have been looking forward to summer sports! We look forward to seeing everyone at some ball games this summer! If you have any questions please email our new AD at meggon.jacobs@northiowa.org.

Today we said a socially distanced goodbye to some pretty amazing people. Retirees shown here: Brad and Loree Huntington, Sue Peake, JoAnn DeBoer, Kim Ostermann, and Sheryl Davids (not pictured: Rox Steffensen). See some of their parting words of wisdom: https://spark.adobe.com/video/jB0ebBZ8GMiqc

We also said farewell to many talented educators who are moving on, including HS Principal Keri Bergeson and Chad Hinders, who has taught at NI for 20 years — see more here: https://spark.adobe.com/video/cX1eDdm5dBsQZ We have been fortunate to have these educators share their talents with us!

(Thanks to Elementary Principal Shawn Miller for making the videos we shared with you! )

Online education looks different at different grade levels and in different subject matters. As we wind down this unusual school year, thanks to our teachers for keeping it fresh and fun this spring!

A few of our students have said they appreciate how Mr. Wilderman has been keeping up with his fun "Fire Friday" experiments. Here's a look into this weeks': FIRE WRITING It's a great example of how both science and online learning are works in progress requiring dedication, problem-solving, patience, and lots of resources. Thanks to Mr. Wilderman for opening up his classroom and letting us share this with you!

Explanation: https://youtu.be/aYW3JK2nNME
Experiment: https://youtu.be/PmdGveXi79U
Another Example (from another teacher, in pre-Covid times): https://youtu.be/ehJyCBNtiGE

And just because it's pretty cool, here's one more of Mr. Wilderman's Fire Friday experiments, from earlier in our time apart, the Boom Bucket: https://youtu.be/IYwqSYKmO2g

post_text:
This week our North Iowa student athletes would have been busy traveling to North Union, Garner-Hayfield-Ventura, Belmond-Klemme, Forest City, West Hancock, Rice Lake Golf Club, and hosting a home track meet and golf triangular. Along with those athletes would have been coaches, bus drivers, officials, parents, siblings, peers, community members and many more! It's hard on all the above. But the gorgeous sky, green grass and stadium lights tonight let us know that better days are ahead.

To our Class of 2020, these lights were also for you! We love you and are proud of you!
#lightupIA #bisonpride #bisonstrong

There were more than a few current NI students and alumni in the reportedly more than 250 cars that assembled tonight to show support for the Kettwick family as Troy (NI alum, '13) is hospitalized in the Twin Cities.

It's hard to believe just a few weeks ago, Troy's mom Carole, our retired choir and business teacher, was playing piano for our high school musical practices (shown below) -- life has changed a lot since then. These are tough times, but it's great to see our Bison family pull together to support Troy and his family, including his fiance Rachel Rolling, also an NI alum.

We've been remiss in sharing some of the cool things that have been happening at North Iowa -- and now, when we're less able to be together, it seems like a golden opportunity to share these things with you to keep us connected!

The RSVP program is a great opportunity to get community members involved and to give our elementary students more chances to read. Big thanks to our teachers (especially first grade teachers Mrs. Huntington and Mrs. Kardoes) who help coordinate this program at NI and to our community volunteers who come in and read with students each week!

post_text: On Wednesday, our 2nd, 3rd, and 4th grade students were fortunate enough to learn about the Iditarod race and sled dogs, with a special presentation by Marla Betz, a sled-dog aficionado and retired high school social studies teacher from Forest City. Special thanks to Ms. Betz for sharing her expertise and enthusiasm for this subject -- our students really enjoyed it!

post_text: Our 5th graders are working on creating “Esti-Mysteries” that blend estimation with computation — and Mrs. Donahue’s kindergarteners got in on the fun by creating an estimation challenge of their own. How many beads will fit in this fun Bison bottle? After a little guessing, kindergartens used the skills of counting by 10 and making tally marks to find the answer! Now . . . let’s see if 5th grade can make some clues to help you guess!

Kelso, who wrestles as part of the Forest City team, will advance to Districts next week, to wrestle for a chance to go to State. The close-up below is from an earlier meet -- check out a great action shot and podium pose of Kelso as part of the Globe Gazette's coverage here:

Congrats to our students who were honored at our elementary PBIS recognition last week! While we have a lot of students who follow our Bison Expectations of being respectful, responsible and safe, these students stood out to their teachers. We also honored our elementary counselor, Ms. Knott.

This PBIS album also includes . . .
- Some 1st graders enjoying a reward of Makerspace time creating a puppet theater (Thanks to teacher Dee Hobbs and makerpsace facilitator Kim Ostermann for making this possible -- and to Kim for taking the photos to share with you!)
- A 2nd grade earned reward of "PET DAY" on 1.29.20 (Thanks to teachers Rebecca Murray and Mollie Sorber for making this possible, and to Sheryl Davids for sharing these photos with us!)
- NIHS fall celebration 10.21, p.m.
- NIMS fall celebration 10.21, a.m.
- A fall buying day at the PBIS MS store, hosted in Mr. Huntington's office

We shared with you a few months ago that our own senior Kylie Buns is acting as a spokesperson for LifeServe. Take a look at her now-published story on the link below.

And mark your calendar for North Iowa's next LifeServe Blood Drive on March 31, 2-6:30 p.m.!

https://www.lifeservebloodcenter.org/2020/01/recipient-family-gives-back-following-massive-transfusions/?fbclid=IwAR0rGBhbXnQCwof5sD5K5_HYlBSJvDTX6Yy2THf6-bus9i4sC9cnfEbHm2w

Thanks to Kylie's mom, Teresa, for keeping us up-to-date about Kylie's work with LifeServe -- and for school nurse Deb Aukes and her team of student volunteers for organizing our semi-annual blood drives!

NIHS Basketball Coaches & Players will be holding a MINI NBA CLINIC on Saturdays in January (11th, 18th, and 25th) for ALL boys and girls in grades 3-6
9:00-10:00 for 3rd & 4th grade
10:00-11:00am for 5th and 6th grade

During this time, participants will be taught the basics of playing basketball including defense, shooting, dribbling, passing and other drills to improve their skills. There will be a time at the end of the session for games coached by the high school players. There is no need to sign up, just come and have some fun.

Please contact any of the high school basketball coaches with questions.
Joel Price, Head Boys Coach: joel.price@northiowa.org
Rick Meyer Head Girls Coach: meyerr@northiowa.org
Eric Krull, Dan Frerichs, Rebecca Murray assistant coaches

The North Iowa Booster Club along with Farmers Trust and Savings Bank is sponsoring a FREE THROW CONTEST
WHEN: Sunday, January 26th, 2020
WHERE: North Iowa High School Gymnasium
TIME: Warm-Ups 1:00 p.m. / Contest 1:30 p.m.

Medals and Ribbons will be awarded to the top three places in each age division.

Parents are responsible for picking up their children after the contest, and must fill out a free throw registration application: https://www.northiowa.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/FREE-THROW-CONTEST-2020-January.pdf

post_text: Students K-12 teamed up to study coding as part of the Hour of Code December 12.
text: Students K-12 teamed up to study coding as part of the Hour of Code December 12.

shared_text:
North Iowa Community School District added 77 new photos.
January 1 at 5:10 PM ·

On December 12, our students K-12 teamed up to learn a little about coding as part of a world-wide event known as Hour of Code. Our local event, which featured a large group coding session of some dance moves and then individual coding exploration, was organized by computer science teacher Arin Anderson and led by experienced students.

Thanks to Kim Ostermann and Loree Huntington for sharing some of these photos with us to share with you!

post_text: Our quiz bowl team finished another successful season on Saturday, in Spirit Lake. The varsity team below was one of four teams to make the playoffs from a field of 20. After a thrilling come-from-behind surge in their final match-up, these four seniors narrowly missed making the championship round. Our JV team also did well, finishing 5th of about 20. Congrats to everyone on the NI quiz bowl team and coach Jon Potter!
text: Our quiz bowl team finished another successful season on Saturday, in Spirit Lake. The varsity team below was one of four teams to make the playoffs from a field of 20. Congrats to everyone on the NI quiz bowl team and coach Jon Potter!
